Section section_02 (Chars 9138–12774):
Section Summary: In his later years, Spencer was disheartened to see that his social and political doctrines were not widely accepted by a new generation of thinkers. Despite this, he had established a respected position in the philosophy of life and mind. Spencer's philosophy emphasized the concept of evolution as a universal principle, governed by natural laws and processes, which he believed applied to all aspects of existence, including matter, mind, and society. He sought to provide a unified explanation of all phenomena in terms of matter, motion, and force, and believed that even mental evolution could be interpreted in these terms. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy acknowledged the limitations of human understanding, recognizing that some mysteries, such as the ultimate reality, may be beyond human comprehension.
